1-20: Aggregate Functions


SUM() – Returns the sum of values
AVG() – Returns the average of values
COUNT() – Counts the number of rows
MIN() – Returns the minimum value
MAX() – Returns the maximum value
GROUP_CONCAT() – Concatenates values in a group (MySQL)
STRING_AGG() – Concatenates values in a group (SQL Server, PostgreSQL)
VARIANCE() – Returns the variance of values
STDDEV() – Returns the standard deviation of values
MEDIAN() – Returns the median value (Some databases)
PERCENTILE_CONT() – Calculates percentile (SQL Server, PostgreSQL)
PERCENTILE_DISC() – Returns a discrete percentile value
CUME_DIST() – Cumulative distribution within a partition
DENSE_RANK() – Returns rank without gaps
RANK() – Returns rank with gaps
NTILE(n) – Divides rows into n buckets

Windows Functions

FIRST_VALUE() – Returns the first value in an ordered set
LAST_VALUE() – Returns the last value in an ordered set
LAG() – Accesses previous row value
LEAD() – Accesses next row value

21-40: String Functions

CONCAT() – Concatenates strings
CONCAT_WS() – Concatenates with a separator
SUBSTRING() – Extracts part of a string
LEFT() – Extracts left part of a string
RIGHT() – Extracts right part of a string
LENGTH() – Returns string length
CHAR_LENGTH() – Returns character length
UPPER() – Converts to uppercase
LOWER() – Converts to lowercase
TRIM() – Removes spaces from both ends
LTRIM() – Removes spaces from the left
RTRIM() – Removes spaces from the right
REPLACE() – Replaces part of a string
TRANSLATE() – Replaces multiple characters at once
REVERSE() – Reverses a string
LPAD() – Pads a string from the left
RPAD() – Pads a string from the right
INSTR() – Finds the position of a substring
POSITION() – Returns position of substring (ANSI SQL)
FORMAT() – Formats numbers as strings

41-60: Date & Time Functions

NOW() – Returns the current timestamp
CURRENT_TIMESTAMP() – Returns the current timestamp
CURRENT_DATE() – Returns the current date
CURRENT_TIME() – Returns the current time
SYSDATE() – Returns the system date (Oracle, MySQL)
GETDATE() – Returns current date and time (SQL Server)
DATE() – Extracts date from a timestamp
TIME() – Extracts time from a timestamp
YEAR() – Extracts year from a date
MONTH() – Extracts month from a date
DAY() – Extracts day from a date
HOUR() – Extracts hour from a timestamp
MINUTE() – Extracts minute from a timestamp
SECOND() – Extracts second from a timestamp
EXTRACT() – Extracts parts of a date/time
DATEADD() – Adds a value to a date (SQL Server)
DATEDIFF() – Returns the difference between two dates
TIMESTAMPDIFF() – Returns difference between timestamps (MySQL)
TO_DATE() – Converts a string to date format (Oracle, PostgreSQL)
TO_CHAR() – Converts date to a string format

61-80: Conditional & Case Functions

CASE – Conditional logic in SQL
COALESCE() – Returns the first non-null value
NULLIF() – Returns NULL if two values are equal
IF() – Conditional function (MySQL)
IFNULL() – Returns alternative value if NULL (MySQL)
ISNULL() – Checks if a value is NULL (SQL Server)
NVL() – Returns alternative value if NULL (Oracle)
NVL2() – Returns different values based on NULL condition (Oracle)
DECODE() – Conditional function in Oracle
IIF() – Inline IF function (SQL Server)
ABS() – Returns absolute value
CEIL() – Rounds up to nearest integer
FLOOR() – Rounds down to nearest integer
ROUND() – Rounds to specified decimal places
TRUNC() – Truncates to a given decimal place
POWER() – Raises a number to a power
SQRT() – Returns the square root
MOD() – Returns remainder of division
SIGN() – Returns the sign of a number
RADIANS() – Converts degrees to radians

81-100: Miscellaneous Functions

UUID() – Generates a unique identifier
RAND() – Generates a random number
MD5() – Hashes a string using MD5
SHA1() – Hashes a string using SHA-1
SHA2() – Hashes a string using SHA-2
JSON_EXTRACT() – Extracts JSON values (MySQL, PostgreSQL)
JSONB_EXTRACT_PATH() – Extracts JSON values (PostgreSQL)
REGEXP_LIKE() – Matches a regular expression
REGEXP_REPLACE() – Replaces part of a string using regex
REGEXP_SUBSTR() – Extracts a substring using regex
CAST() – Converts one data type to another
CONVERT() – Converts data types (SQL Server, MySQL)
UNION() – Combines result sets without duplicates
UNION ALL() – Combines result sets with duplicates
INTERSECT() – Returns common records from two queries
EXCEPT() – Returns records from first query but not second
LATERAL() – Allows subqueries to reference columns in the main query
CROSS APPLY() – Joins a table with a table-valued function (SQL Server)
OUTER APPLY() – Works like a left join with table-valued functions
PIVOT() – Converts rows into columns
